    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I apologize for the excessive goblin metaphors; I can certainly explain the atmospheric mechanics of a cold front without the goblin interference.\n\nWhen a cold front moves in, it is essentially a boundary where a dense, cold air mass is advancing and sliding underneath a lighter, warmer air mass. Because cold air is denser than warm air, it acts like a wedge that forces the warmer air to rise rapidly. As this warm air ascends, it expands and cools adiabatically, causing the water vapor within it to condense into clouds and precipitation.\n\nOnce the front passes, the high-pressure system associated with the cold air mass takes over, bringing stable, colder temperatures and often clearing skies. The rapid temperature drop you experienced is a direct result of this dense, cold air replacing the less dense, warmer air at the surface.",
      "source": "target",
